title: Strategies for adding 2-digit numbers
description: Sal goes through multiple strategies for adding 2-digit numbers.

title: Geometry transformations
description:
In this topic you will learn about the most useful math concept for creating video game graphics: geometric transformations, specifically translations, rotations, reflections, and dilations.

You will learn how to perform the transformations, and how to map one figure into another using these transformations.

title: Congruence
description: Learn what it means for two figures to be congruent, and how to determine whether two figures are congruent or not. Use this immensely important concept to prove various geometric theorems about triangles and parallelograms.

title: Constant angular momentum when no net torque
description: Just like how linear momentum is constant when there's no net force, angular momentum is constant where there's no net torque

title: Analytic geometry
description: In analytic geometry, also known as coordinate geometry, we think about geometric objects on the coordinate plane. For example, we can see that opposite sides of a parallelogram are parallel by by writing a linear equation for each side and seeing that the slopes are the same.

title: Angular momentum of an extended object
description: In this video David derives and shows how to use the formula for the angular momentum of an extended object.

title: Why biodiversity is distributed unevenly
description: Factors that influence the global distribution of biodiversity. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Ball hits rod angular momentum example
description: David explains how a mass can have angular momentum even if it is traveling along a straight line. Then David shows how to solve the conservation of angular momentum problem where a ball hits a rod which can rotate.

title: Threats to biodiversity
description: Examine the local and global threats to biodiversity that are caused by human activities. Many of the negative impacts start as regional, but easily add up to affect the entire planet. This content is provided by the California Academy of Sciences.

title: Ecological succession
description: Communities are dynamic and change over time, and we can observe this process with particular clarity after a disturbance or on new land. Learn about  primary and secondary succession, as well as pioneer species.

title: Human activities that threaten biodiversity
description: Human activities that cause a loss of biodiversity. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Ecological succession
description: Succession as progressive change in an ecological community. Primary vs. secondary succession. The idea of a climax community.

title: How does climate change affect biodiversity?
description: Effects of climate change on biodiversity. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Intro to ecosystems
description: What is an ecosystem? Well...it can be something as small as a tide pool,or as huge as the Amazon rainforest. But whatever size it may be, an ecosystem is made up of a community (populations of species interacting) plus their physical environment. Learn about different types of ecosystems and how energy flows through ecological communities.

title: Demystifying ocean acidification and biodiversity impacts
description: Why rising carbon dioxide levels in the atmosphere affect the acidity of the ocean, and what the consequences are for marine life. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: What is an ecosystem?
description: Learn what an ecosystem is, how energy and matter move through ecosystems, and what makes an ecosystem stable.

title: Absolute value & piecewise functions
description: Learn how to solve absolute value equations and how to graph absolute value functions.

title: Simple harmonic motion
description: Ever watch a slinky gyrate back and forth.  This is harmonic motion (a special class of oscillatory motion).  In this tutorial we'll see how we can model and deal with this type of phenomena.

title: Flow of energy and matter through ecosystems
description: Seeing how energy and matter flows and is recycled from primary producers (autotrophs) to primary, secondary and tertiary consumers.

title: Polynomials
description: Learn how to add, subtract, multiply, and divide polynomial expressions. For example, write (2x+3)(x-1) as 2x²+x-3.

title: Intuition about simple harmonic oscillators
description: David defines what it means for something to be a simple harmonic oscillator and gives some intuition about why oscillators do what they do as well as where the speed, acceleration, and force will be largest and smallest.

title: Protecting biodiversity
description: Research, education, individual action, and public policy all have important roles to play in protecting biodiversity. That means there's a lot you, personally, can do to preserve species and ecosystems - whoever you may be, and wherever you may live! This content is provided by the California Academy of Sciences.

title: Food chains & food webs
description: How food chains and food webs represent the flow of energy and matter. Trophic levels and efficiency of energy transfer.

title: Conservation and the race to save biodiversity
description: Different approaches to conservation and how they can protect species and habitats. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Irrational numbers
description: Learn about irrational numbers and how to identify them.

title: The water cycle
description: Learn how water moves through Earth's ecosystems.

title: Conic sections
description: Learn about two basic conic sections and their equations: Circle and Parabola.

title: Basic shapes
description: Learn the names of basic shapes, including circles, triangles, squares, and rectangles.

title: Subtraction within 100
description: Learn to subtract two-digit numbers like 47 and 39.

title: Adding 1s, 10s, and 100s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems by adding ones, tens, and hundreds.

title: Multiply by 8
description: Multiply 8 times a number less than or equal to 10.

title: Divide by 4
description: Divide by 4.  Quotients are less than or equal to 10.

title: Volume
description: Estimate the volume of items.  Solve word problems involving volume.

title: Creating bar graphs
description: Practice creating bar graphs to represent data.

title: Reading bar graphs: Harry Potter
description: Sal interprets a bar graph.

title: Definition of amplitude and period
description: David defines the terms amplitude and period for simple harmonic motion and shows how to find them on a graph.

title: Factorization
description: Learn how to write polynomial expressions as the product of linear factors. For example, write x^2+3x+2 as (x+1)(x+2).

title: Equation for simple harmonic oscillators
description: David explains the equation that represents the motion of a simple harmonic oscillator and solves an example problem.

title: Energy flow & primary productivity
description: Learn about primary productivity, the (in)efficiency of energy transfer between trophic levels, and how to read ecological pyramids.

title: Period dependence for mass on spring
description: David explains what affects the period of a mass on a spring (i.e. mass and spring constant). He also explains what does not affect the period of a mass on a spring (i.e. amplitude and gravitational acceleration).

title: Phase constant
description: In this video David explains how a phase constant can be used in order to shift the graph of an oscillator left or right.

title: Levels of biodiversity
description: Learn how to recognize the genetic, ecosystem, and evolutionary levels of biodiversity. Along with species richness, these levels play crucial roles in conservation. Content provided by the California Academy of Sciences.

title: Biogeochemical cycles
description: "Atoms get recycled." That may not sound too exciting. But think of it this way: some of the atoms in your body right now were once almost certainly part of trees, rocks, various animals, other human beings, and even dinosaurs! Learn more about how matter is recycled in Earth's ecosystems and why the water, carbon, nitrogen, and phosphorous cycles are so important to living things.

title: Pendulums
description: David explains how a pendulum can be treated as a simple harmonic oscillator, and then explains what affects, as well as what does not affect, the period of a pendulum.

title: Genes and biodiversity
description: How does the gene pool contribute to biodiversity? Learn how genetic diversity within populations contributes to species survival. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Intro to biogeochemical cycles
description: Get an overview of how atoms are recycled through Earth's ecosystems via biogeochemical cycles.

title: Exponential growth & decay
description: Learn how to analyze and manipulate exponential functions and expressions in order to study their rate of change.

title: Ecosystem biodiversity
description: Are all coral reefs the same?  Each regional ecosystem has its own assemblage of species and each contributes uniquely to global biodiversity. Explore why ecosystem diversity is important for conservation decisions. Video by California Academy of Sciences.

title: Biogeochemical cycles overview
description: Introduction to how water, carbon, nitrogen, and phosphorus are cycled through ecosystems.

title: Introduction to harmonic motion
description: Harmonic motion refers to the motion an oscillating mass experiences when the restoring force is proportional to the ​displacement, but in opposite directions. Harmonic motion is periodic and can be represented by a sine wave with constant frequency and amplitude. An example of this is a weight bouncing on a spring.

title: Similarity
description: Learn what it means for two figures to be similar, and how to determine whether two figures are similar or not. Use this concept to prove geometric theorems and solve some problems with polygons.

title: Levels of biodiversity
description: Test your knowledge on the levels of biodiversity!

title: Harmonic motion part 2 (calculus)
description: We test whether Acos(wt) can describe the motion of the mass on a spring by substituting into the differential equation F=-kx

title: The water cycle
description: How the sun's energy drives the water cycle on Earth.

title: Right triangles & trigonometry
description: Triangles are not always right (although they are never wrong), but when they are it opens up an exciting world of possibilities.  Not only are right triangles cool in their own right (pun intended), they are the basis of very important ideas in analytic geometry (the distance between two points in space) and trigonometry.

title: Harmonic motion part 3 (no calculus)
description: Figuring out the period, frequency, and amplitude of the harmonic motion of a mass attached to a spring.

title: The carbon cycle
description: Learn how carbon moves through Earth's ecosystems and how human activities are altering the carbon cycle.

title: Solid geometry
description: Extend your knowledge about two-dimensional shapes to three dimensions!

title: Introduction to mechanical waves
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn the definition of a wave and the difference between transverse and longitudinal waves. You'll also learn the definition of the basic terms used to characterize waves; amplitude, period, frequency, and wavelength.

title: The carbon cycle
description: Overview of how carbon is recycled through our biosphere in the carbon cycle.

title: Circles
description: Explore, prove, and apply important properties of circles that have to do with things like arc length, radians, inscribed angles, and tangents.

title: Introduction to waves
description: Introduction to transverse and longitudinal waves

title: The nitrogen cycle
description: The key role of microbes in nitrogen fixation. How overuse of nitrogen-containing fertilizers can cause algal blooms.

title: Properties of periodic waves
description: Amplitude, period, frequency and wavelength of periodic waves. How to calculate wave velocity.

title: Multiplication intro
description: Welcome to the concept of multiplication.

title: Time
description: Learn how to tell time on analog clocks.

title: The fundamental theorem of calculus and definite integrals
Topic B: Lesson 8: Adding and subtracting polynomials with 2 variables
Animal behavior
description: How do songbirds learn to sing? Why do ants follow invisible lines to sources of food? What are dogs trying to accomplish when they mark their territory? Learn about these and many other fascinating, diverse, and sometimes bizarre examples of animal behavior.

title: The nitrogen cycle
description: How nitrogen is recycled in our biosphere in the nitrogen cycle, including nitrogen fixation.

title: Intro to animal behavior
description: What exactly counts as behavior? What triggers behaviors? Are they hard-wired in animals' genes, or learned based on experience?

title: Probability
description: Few things are certain in life. Probability gives us an idea of the likelihood or unlikelihood of different outcomes.

title: The equation of a wave
description: In this video David shows how to determine the equation of a wave, how that equation works, and what the equation represents.

title: The phosphorous cycle
description: The slow cycling of phosphorous through the biosphere. How phosphorous-containing fertilizers can cause aquatic dead zones.

title: Innate behaviors
description: Learn about behaviors that are pre-programmed into an animal's genes, including reflexes and fixed action patterns.

title: Sound
description: In these videos and articles you'll see visualizations of the propagation of sound waves, along with a visual definition of a sound wave's amplitude, period, frequency, and wavelength. You'll also learn how the speed of sound depends on the different characteristics of the medium. It will be shown how Mach numbers characterize faster than sound travel and their relationship to sonic booms. Also, you'll learn about the decibel scale, why sounds get softer, and how ultrasound medical imaging works.

title: Phosphorous cycle
description: Introduction to the phosphorous cycle. How phosphorus is recycled from phosphate to ATP and DNA.

title: Production of sound
description: Sound is vibrating air. But how does the air start vibrating?

title: Learned behaviors
description: Habituation, imprinting, classical conditioning, operant conditioning, and cognitive learning.

title: Eutrophication and dead zones
description: How eutrophication, caused by extra nutrients in runoff, can lead to dead zones.

title: Animal communication
description: Visit us (http://www.khanacademy.org/science/healthcare-and-medicine) for health and medicine content or (http://www.khanacademy.org/test-prep/mcat) for MCAT related content. These videos do not provide medical advice and are for informational purposes only. The videos are not intended to be a substitute for professional medical advice, diagnosis or treatment. Always seek the advice of a qualified health provider with any questions you may have regarding a medical condition. Never disregard professional medical advice or delay in seeking it because of something you have read or seen in any Khan Academy video.

title: Sound Properties: Amplitude, period, frequency, wavelength
description: How to find the amplitude, period, frequency, and wavelength for a sound wave

title: Animal communication
description: Learn how animals communicate with visual, sound, touch, and chemical signals.

title: Functions
description: A great cook knows how to take basic ingredients and prepare a delicious meal. In this topic, you will become function-chefs! You will learn how to combine functions with arithmetic operations and how to compose functions. You will also learn how to transform functions in ways that shift, reflect, or stretch their graphs. Finally, you will learn about inverse functions and how to find them!

title: Biogeochemical cycles
description: Test your knowledge of biogeochemical cycles!

title: Relative speed of sound in solids, liquids, and gases
description: Sounds travels at different speeds in different media

title: Polynomials
description: Learn how to manipulate polynomials in order to prove identities and find the zeros of those polynomials. Use this knowledge to solve polynomial equations and graph polynomial functions. Learn about symmetry of functions.

title: Biogeography
description: Have you ever noticed that different types of animals and plants are found in different places? Learn about some of the factors behind patterns of species distribution and abundance.

title: Radical relationships
description: In this topic you will learn how to solve radical equations (which are equations with radical expressions in them) while avoiding extraneous solutions. You will also learn how to graph radical functions.

title: Decibel Scale
description: We often use this logarithmic scale to describe the intensity of sound

title: Rational relationships
description: Rational expressions are like fractions, but instead of integers in the numerator and the denominator, you have variable expressions! Learn how to work with such expressions. Namely, simplify, add, subtract, multiply, and divide them (much like fractions!). Then, solve some equations with rational expressions in them, and analyze the behavior of rational functions.

title: Why do sounds get softer?
description: Let's think about why sounds would have to get softer as you get further from the source

title: Exponentials & logarithms
description: Learn about logarithms, which are the inverses of exponents. Use logarithms to solve various equations. Then analyze both logarithmic and exponential functions and their graphs.

title: Doppler effect formula when source is moving away
description: Let's look at the case where the source is moving away from the listener

title: Pressure at a depth in a fluid
description: Sal derives the formula to determine the pressure at a specific depth in a fluid.

title: Density and Pressure
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn the definitions of density and specific gravity. You'll also learn the definition of pressure, how it relates to force and area, and how to determine the pressure within a fluid. The difference between absolute and gauge pressure will also be discussed.

title: Tolerance ranges of species
description: Abiotic (non-living) factors that influence where a species can live.

title: Ultrasound medical imaging
description: Ultrasound medical imaging (also known as sonography) is a diagnostic imaging tool that uses high-frequency sound waves to create images of structures in the body. Ultrasound images are captured in ​real time​ using an external probe and ultrasound gel placed directly on the skin. They can show things that a still image like an X-ray cannot, such as blood flow or organ movement. Ultrasound images are highly useful in the diagnosis and treatment of many diseases.

title: Specific gravity
description: In this video David explains what specific gravity means. He also shows how to calculate the value for specific gravity and use it to determine the percent of an object that will be submerged while floating.

title: Trigonometry
description: Learn about the definition of the basic trigonometric functions (sin(x), cos(x), and tan(x)), and use advanced trigonometric functions for various purposes.

title: The Doppler effect
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how the Doppler effect causes a change in the measured frequency of a moving source of sound or moving sound detector. You'll also learn how to calculate the observed frequency using the formula for the Doppler effect when dealing with either a moving source of sound or a moving sound detector.

title: Climate
description: Global, regional, and local factors that influence climate. How climate affects where species are found.

title: Pressure and Pascal's principle (part 1)
description: Sal explains the difference between liquids and gasses (both fluids). He then starts a calculation of the work done on a liquid in a U-shaped container.

title: Advanced equations & functions
description: Solve advanced equations by graphing. Interpret advanced features of functions (like symmetry, end behavior, and periodicity) in terms of their context, and compare features of various types of functions.

title: Doppler effect introduction
description: Learn about the Doppler effect and how it explains the change in frequency of a wave when its source and an observer are moving.

title: Pressure and Pascal's principle (part 2)
description: Sal finishes the calculation of work to determine the mechanical advantage in a U-shaped tube. He also explains pressure and Pascal's Principle.

title: Doppler effect formula for observed frequency
description: Let's derive the formula for how the perceived frequency of a sound changes when its source is moving toward you

title: Study Design
description: Getting reliable data is vital if we want to make correct conclusions.The process of collecting data through studies involves sampling, observations, surveys, and experiments.

title: Binomial probability
description: If you roll five dice, what’s the probability that three of them show a 6? In a group of 20 strangers, what’s the probability that more than half of them were born in the summer? Learn about binomial probability to answer these types of problems.

title: When the source and the wave move at the same velocity
description: What happens when both the listener and the source are moving together?

title: Finding height of fluid in a barometer
description: Using our understanding of fluid pressure to figure out the height of a column of mercury.

title: Normal distributions
description: A Normal distribution is a very special and common distribution that is fundamental to learning about statistics. Normal distributions describe many real world phenomena from scores on exams to lengths of wings on bugs.

title: Doppler effect for a moving observer
description: What happens when just the observer is moving?

title: Body structure & homeostasis
description: What makes a tissue different from an organ? How does your stomach collaborate with your small intestine to make sure you get nutrients? And most important, how do the systems of your body keep things like your temperature and blood pH from getting too high or too low? Keep reading and watching to find answers to all of these questions!

title: Buoyant Force and Archimedes' Principle
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how pressure variations cause a buoyant force on a submerged object and how to calculate the value of the buoyant force. You'll also learn the meaning of Archimedes' principle.

title: Doppler effect: reflection off a moving object
description: Does the doppler effect still apply when sound is being reflected off a moving object?

title: Tissues, organs, & organ systems
description: Learn about the main tissue types and organ systems of the body and how they work together.

title: Archimedes principle and buoyant force
description: Introduction to Archimedes' principle and buoyant force.

title: Wave interference
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how standing waves are produced and how to determine the wavelength and frequency of the different harmonics of standing waves produced in an open open tube or an open closed tube.

title: Adding 1s and 10s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems like 23+4 and 23+40.

title: Measuring length
description: Learn how to measure length using unit squares and rulers.

title: Skip-counting
description: Learn to count by fives, tens, and hundreds.

title: Comparing and estimating length
description: Learn how to compare and estimate length.

title: Divide by 5
description: Divide by 5.  Quotients are less than or equal to 10.

title: States of matter
description: Introduction to the states or phases of matter.

title: What is buoyant force?
description: Why the heck do things float?

title: Homeostasis
description: Learn how organisms maintain homeostasis, or a stable internal environment.

title: Wave interference
description: David explains wave interference and solves a few examples to find the value of the total wave when two wave pulses overlap.

title: Body structure and homeostasis
description: Test your knowledge of body structure and homeostasis!

title: Buoyant force example problems
description: A couple of problems involving Archimedes' principle and buoyant forces.

title: Constructive and Destructive interference
description: In this video David explains what constructive and destructive interference means as well as how path length differences and pi shifts affect the interference.

title: Metabolism & thermoregulation
description: You may think of metabolism as something that humans have (such as a fast or a slow metabolism). But metabolism is just the sum total of chemical reactions that occur in an organism's body, and all organisms must metabolize to keep their bodies running. Learn more about metabolism and how it's connected to thermoregulation (temperature regulation) in different species of animals.

title: Fluid Dynamics
description: Flowing fluids behave different from static fluids. In these videos and articles you'll learn about volume flow rate and the equation of continuity. You'll also learn how Bernoulli's principle and Bernoulli's equation relate the pressure and speed of a flowing fluid. The effects of turbulence and viscosity will also be discussed.

title: Metabolic rate
description: Metabolism of endotherms and ectotherms. Basal metabolic rate and standard metabolic rate. How metabolic rate varies with body size and activity level.

title: Standing waves on strings
description: David explains how and why standing waves occur, and well as how to determine the wavelengths for a standing wave on a string.

title: Volume flow rate and equation of continuity
description: Sal introduces the notion of moving fluids and laminar flow. Then he uses the incompressibility of a liquid to show that the volume flow rate (flux) must remain constant. Sal then derives the equation of continuity in terms of the area and speed.

title: Endotherms & ectotherms
description: The difference between endotherms and ectotherms. How to read graphs related to endotherms and ectotherms.

title: Standing waves in open tubes
description: Find out why a flute makes such specific notes

title: What is volume flow rate?
description: You know all about the motion of individual objects. Now, let's talk about how to analyze the motion of a fluid.

title: What is the first law of thermodynamics?
description: Learn what the first law of thermodynamics is and how to use it.

title: Proof: S (or entropy) is a valid state variable
description: Proof that S (or entropy) is a valid state variable.

title: 2015 AP Biology free response, 1d-e
description: Light-dark activity cycle of mutant mice and evolutionary implications.

title: Pith ball electroscope
description: Primitive device for measuring electrostatic force

title: Temperature regulation strategies
description: How behavior, anatomy, and physiology help animals regulate body temperature.

title: Standing waves in closed tubes
description: Find out why you can make music by blowing into empty bottles

title: Bernoulli's equation (part 1)
description: This is the first of two videos where Sal derives Bernoulli's equation.

title: Thermoregulation
description: Test your knowledge of thermoregulation!

title: Beat frequency
description: David explains what beat frequency means, how to find it, and solves a sample problem involving beat frequency.

title: Bernoulli's equation (part 2)
description: This is the second of two videos where Sal derives Bernoulli's equation. In the second half of the video Sal also begins an example problem where liquid exits a hole in a container.

title: Bernoulli's equation (part 3)
description: Sal finishes the example problem where liquid exits a hole in a container.

title: Derivation of beat frequency formula
description: In this video David derives the formula for beat frequency.

title: Bernoulli's equation (part 4)
description: Clarification of, and more thoughts on, the Bernoulli's equation example problem where liquid exits a hole in a container.

title: Bernoulli's example problem
description: Sal solves a Bernoulli's equation example problem where fluid is moving through a pipe of varying diameter.

title: What is Bernoulli's equation?
description: This equation will give you the powers to analyze a fluid flowing up and down through all kinds of different tubes.

title: Viscosity and Poiseuille flow
description: David explains the concept of viscosity, viscous force, and Poiseuille's law.

title: Temperature, kinetic theory, and the ideal gas law
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn about the Celsius and Kelvin temperature scales. The definition of a mole of a substance will be given. You'll also learn how the ideal gas law relates the pressure, volume, and temperature of a gas. Lastly, you'll learn how the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution gives the probability of finding a gas molecule moving at a specific speed.

title: Work from expansion
description: How a system can do work by expanding

title: Inflammatory response
description: Overview of the inflammatory response.

title: Hundreds
description: Learn to see three-digit numbers as hundreds, tens, and ones.

title: Repeated addition
description: Adding the same number to itself over and over

title: Teens
description: Learn how teen numbers work.

title: Comparing shapes
description: Learn to compare shapes based on their features and position.

title: Addition and subtraction
description: In this topic, we will add and subtract whole numbers. The topic starts with 1+1=2 and goes through adding and subtracting within 1000.  We will cover regrouping, borrowing, and word problems.

title: Turbulence at high velocities and Reynold's number
description: In this video David explains how the Reynold's number allows you to determine the speed at which fluid flow becomes turbulent.

title: Thermodynamics part 1: Molecular theory of gases
description: Intuition of how gases generate pressure in a container and why pressure x volume is proportional to the combined kinetic energy of the molecules in the volume.

title: Multiplication and division
description: In this topic, we will multiply and divide whole numbers. The topic starts with 1-digit multiplication and division and goes through multi-digit problems.  We will cover regrouping, remainders, and word problems.

title: Venturi effect and Pitot tubes
description: David explains the Venturi effect and the role and function of Pitot tubes.

title: Thermodynamics part 2: Ideal gas law
description: To begin, Sal solves a constant temperature problem using PV=PV. Then he relates temperature to kinetic energy of a gas. In the second half of the video, he derives the ideal gas law.

title: Negative numbers
description: Learn about numbers below 0 and how they relate to positive numbers.  Add, subtract, multiply and divide negative numbers.

title: Surface Tension and Adhesion
description: David explains the concepts of surface tension, cohesion, and adhesion.

title: Phototropism
description: Phototropism and the role that auxin plays.

title: Capacitance
description: Introduction to the capacitance of a two-plate capacitor.

title: The dot product
description: Introduction to the vector dot product.

title: Composing shapes
description: Practice making shapes from other shapes.

title: Kirchhoff's loop rule
description: Learn how to analyze the voltage in a DC circuit using Kirchhoff loop rule (or voltage law).

title: Naming ionic compounds
description: Practice naming ionic compounds when given the formula

title: Multiplication facts
description: Learn multiplication facts (sometimes called times tables).

title: Multiply by 9
description: Multiply 9 times a number less than or equal to 10.

title: Divide by 6
description: Divide by 6.  Quotients are less than or equal to 10.

title: Intro to fractions
description: Sal divides wholes into equal-sized pieces to create unit fractions.

title: Basic division
description: Divide two numbers.  Quotients are equal to or less than 10.

title: Thermodynamics part 3: Kelvin scale and Ideal gas law example
description: Sal makes the case for the Kelvin scale of temperature and absolute zero by showing that temperature is proportional to kinetic energy. Then he explains that you need to use the Kelvin scale in the ideal gas law. To finish he does a sample ideal gas law problem.

title: Fractions
description: In this topic, we will explore fractions conceptually and add, subtract, multiply, and divide fractions.

title: Thermodynamics part 4: Moles and the ideal gas law
description: Sal explains the concept of a mole. Then he derives the molar version of the ideal gas law PV=nRT, where the gas constant R=831 J/molK.

title: Decimals
description: In this topic, we will learn what a decimal is and how to show it visually and on a number line.  We will also add, subtract, multiply, and divide with decimals.

title: Thermodynamics part 5: Molar ideal gas law problem
description: Sal uses the molar version of the ideal gas law to solve for the number of moles in a gas. He also shows how to convert this answer into number of molecules using Avogadro's number.

title: What is the ideal gas law?
description: Learn how pressure, volume, temperature, and the amount of a gas are related to each other.

title: Circulatory and pulmonary systems
description: As humans, we really like breathing oxygen.  That's because the cells in our body will die if they don't get the oxygen they need to function.  This tutorial describes how gases are exchanged between blood and the atmosphere in our lungs, and how oxygen is then pumped through the body by way of blood and the circulatory system.

title: Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution
description: Using the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution to visualize the distribution of speeds of particles at different temperatures.

title: Lines
description: Learn what lines, line segments, and rays are and how to use them.

title: Puzzles
description: Strengthen your brain with some mind bending riddles and puzzles.

title: Adding 1s and 10s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems like 23+4 and 23+40.

title: Numbers 0 to 120
description: Learn the numbers from 0 to 120.

title: Bar graphs
description: Learn how to read and interpret bar graphs.

title: Comparing and estimating length
description: Learn how to compare and estimate length.

title: Subtracting 1s and 10s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems like 24-3 and 45-30.

title: Multiply by 2
description: Multiply 2 times a number less than or equal to 10.

title: Relating multiplication and division
description: Let's see how multiplication and division are related.

title: Divide by 7
description: Divide by 7.  Quotients are less than or equal to 10.

title: Ideal gas equation: PV = nRT
description: Intuition behind the ideal gas equation: PV=nRT.

title: Cut shapes into equal parts
description: Practice telling if a shape has been divided into equal parts.

title: The lungs and pulmonary system
description: The pulmonary system including the lungs, larynx, trachea, bronchi, bronchioles, alveoli and thoracic diaphragm.

title: What is the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution?
description: In a gas, there are lots of molecules traveling at lots of different speeds. Here's a framework for thinking about that.

title: Specific heat and heat transfer
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn the definition of specific heat and latent heat and how to use them in problem solving. You'll also learn the 3 modes of heat transfer; conduction, convection, and radiation. Lastly, we will look in more depth at how the rate of thermal conduction through a material depends on the material's thickness, conductivity constant, area, and difference in temperature.

title: Circulatory system and the heart
description: Introduction to the circulatory system and the heart.

title: Specific heat and latent heat of fusion and vaporization
description: Defining specific heat, heat of fusion, and heat of vaporization. How to calculate the amount of heat to change the temperature of water and the energy required to change for a phase change.

title: Thermal conduction, convection, and radiation

They are by far the most abundant organisms on Earth, and are our oldest, oddest relatives.

description: Hank introduces us to nonvascular plants - liverworts, hornworts & mosses - which have bizarre features, kooky habits, and strange sex lives. Nonvascular plants inherited their reproductive cycle from algae, but have perfected it to the point where it is now used by all plants in one way or another, and has even left traces in our own reproductive systems.

title: Vascular plants = Winning!
description: Hank introduces us to one of the most diverse and important families in the tree of life - the vascular plants. These plants have found tremendous success and the their secret is also their defining trait: conductive tissues that can take food and water from one part of a plant to another part. Though it sounds simple, the ability to move nutrients and water from one part of an organism to another was a evolutionary breakthrough for vascular plants, allowing them to grow exponentially larger, store food for lean times, and develop features that allowed them to spread farther and faster. Plants dominated the earth long before animals even showed up, and even today hold the world records for the largest, most massive, and oldest organisms on the planet.

title: Meet Carl Stenoien!
description: Meet Carl Stenoien, insect ecologist and decathlete!

title: The plants & the bees: Plant reproduction
description: Hank gets into the dirty details about vascular plant reproduction: they use the basic alternation of generations developed by nonvascular plants 470 million years ago, but they've tricked it out so that it works a whole lot differently compared to the way it did back in the Ordovician swamps where it got its start. Here's how the vascular plants (ferns, gymnosperms and angiosperms) do it.

description: Death is what fungi are all about. By feasting on the deceased remains of almost all organisms on the planet, converting the organic matter back into soil from which new life will spring, they perform perhaps the most vital function in the global food web. Fungi, which thrive on death, make all life possible.

Hank Green teaches you ecology!

The sign convention for positive and negative image distance, object distance, and focal length will be discussed.

title: Minkowski spacetime
description: In a Newtonian world we assume that the passage of time or lengths in space are absolute--that regardless of one's inertial frame of reference, everyone would agree that the same time passed in every frame of reference and that something of a certain length in one frame would be the same length in other frames.  This leads to the speed of light needing to be relative depending on the frame of reference which contradicts observation.  We reconcile observations by loosening our assumptions about absolute space and time.  We explore this through Minkowski spacetime diagrams.

title: Starting to set up a Newtonian path–time diagram
description: We introduce a graph that's a lot like your good old position-vs-time graph—but with a twist!

title: Photons
description: Light can have wave-like or particle-like properties depending on the experiment being done. These "particles" of light are called photons. In this tutorial you'll learn about photon energy and momentum.

title: Visualizing multiple Newtonian path–time diagrams
description: Now that we know what path–time diagrams are, let's see what happens when we bring along a friend!

title: Galilean transformation and contradictions with light

title: Photon Momentum

title: Introduction to special relativity and Minkowski spacetime diagrams
description: Including multiple observers in the "most obvious" way led to some problems. Let's see how we can start to solve those problems by introducing (what we'll later call) Minkowski spacetime diagrams.

title: Photoelectric effect
description: Explaining the photoelectric effect using wave-particle duality, the work function of a metal, and how to calculate the velocity of a photoelectron.

title: Measuring time in meters in Minkowski spacetime
description: As counterintuitive as it might sound, it will become extremely convenient to use the same units for space and time. Happily, we can do that just by multiplying the time axis by c, the speed of light. Here's how.

title: Photoelectric effect
description: Explaining the experiments on the photoelectric effect. How these experiments led to the idea of light behaving as a particle of energy called a photon.

title: Angle of x' axis in Minkowski spacetime

title: Lorentz transformation
description: We'll now put some algebraic meat on our special relativity bone by introducing ourselves to the Lorentz transformation.  Interestingly, Lorentz came up with them before Einstein introduced Special Relativity as a nice way to reconcile some observations, but special relativity gave them real conceptual meat.  The Lorentz transformation is going to allow us to calculate the spacetime coordinates in different frames of reference!

title: Introduction to the Lorentz transformation

description: Review the key concepts and skills for Newton's third law of motion, including how to identify action-reaction pairs.

title: Electric motors
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how electric motors rely on a magnetic force that can cause a torque which rotates a loop of wire. You'll also learn how commutators allow the direction the the current to switch, which causes the motor to continue turning.

title: Identifying centripetal force for cars and satellites
description: Identifying forces or force components acting as the centripetal force for a car driving in a horizontal circle, a car driving in a vertical circle, and a satellite in orbit.

title: Calculating linear momentum and change in momentum
description: Practice finding quantities related to linear momentum  and the change in momentum from word problems.

title: Finding change in gravitational potential energy
description: Practice solving numerically for the change in gravitational potential energy in various scenarios.

title: Identifying force vectors for pendulum: Worked example
description: A worked example finding all force vectors acting on a pendulum moving in a horizontal circle.

title: Momentum and velocity from force vs. time graphs
description: Practice predicting the change in momentum and velocity from force vs. time graphs.

title: Gravitational potential energy and conservative forces review
description: Review the key concepts and equations for gravitational potential energy, conservative forces, and nonconservative forces.

title: Electric potential energy, electric potential, and voltage
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn the difference between electric potential, electric potential energy, and voltage. You'll also learn how to calculate the electric potential at a point in space, electric potential energy between two charges, and voltage between two points in space.

title: Using the kinetic energy equation
description: Practice using the equation for kinetic energy to find mass, velocity, and kinetic energy.

title: Deriving formula for centripetal acceleration from angular velocity
description: Deriving formula for centripetal acceleration in terms of angular velocity. using linear speed formula.

title: Change in centripetal acceleration from change in linear velocity and radius: Worked examples
description: A worked example finding the change in centripetal acceleration from the change in linear speed, and an example finding the change in centripetal acceleration from the change in radius.

title: Kinetic energy review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for kinetic energy.  Understand how kinetic energy can't be negative but the change in kinetic energy can be negative.

title: Magnetic field created by a current
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how the magnetic field created by a long straight wire depends on the current and distance from the wire. You'll also learn how to use the right hand rule to determine the direction of the magnetic field. The magnetic force between two current carrying wires will be discussed as well as the induced current in a wire moving through a magnetic field.

title: Predicting changes in centripetal acceleration
description: Predict how centripetal acceleration changes with radius, linear, and angular velocity.

title: Calculating change in kinetic energy from a force
description: Find the change in kinetic energy from a force using the work energy theorem.

title: Velocity and mass from force vs. position graphs
description: Using F vs. x graphs to analyze motion with kinetic energy and work.

title: Centripetal forces
description: Learn how to identify centripetal forces and how they relate to speed, tension, normal force, and radius.

title: Introduction to centripetal force
description: Introduction to centripetal force, which accelerates an object toward the center of the circular path.

title: Work-energy theorem review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for the work-energy theorem.  Understand how the work-energy theorem only applies to the net work, not the work done by a single source.

title: Identifying centripetal force for ball on string
description: Identifying forces or force components acting as the centripetal force for a ball on a string moving in a horizontal circle.

title: Gravitational potential energy and conservative forces
description: Learn about what gravitational energy means and how it is related to conservative forces such as gravity.

title: Gravity and orbits
description: Gravity and orbits

title: Wave interference
description: In this lesson, we'll discuss how waves can overlap to produce constructive or destructive interference.

title: Change in momentum and speed from force vs. time graphs
description: Practice calculating change in momentum and speed from force vs. time graphs.

title: Spring potential energy and Hooke's law
description: Weighing machines of all sorts employ springs that take a certain amount of force to keep compressed or stretched to a certain point.  Hooke's law will give us all the tools to weigh in on the subject ourselves and spring into action (pun intended)!

title: Centripetal forces review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for centripetal forces, including that centripetal force is the net force in the radial direction.

title: Magnetic flux and Faraday's law
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how magnetic flux depends on magnetic field strength, area, and angle. You'll also learn how Faraday's law states that a changing magnetic flux can cause an induced current. It will be shown how Lenz's law can allow you to find the direction of the induced current. Example problems will also be solved to show how to apply Faraday's law and Lenz's law.

title: Linear momentum review
description: Overview of key terms and equations for linear momentum, including a derivation of Newton's second law from the conservation of linear momentum.

title: Newton's law of gravitation
description: Why does the earth orbit the sun (or does it)? Gravitation defines our everyday life and the structure of the universe.  This tutorial will introduce gravity in the Newtonian sense.

title: Impulse review
description: Overview of key terms and equations related to impulse, including how impulse can be calculated from a force vs. time graph.

title: Power
description: Learn what power means and how we use it in physics to describe the rate of energy transfer.

title: Adding 1s and 10s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems like 23+4 and 23+40.

title: Skip-counting
description: Learn to count by fives, tens, and hundreds.

title: Hundreds
description: Learn to see three-digit numbers as hundreds, tens, and ones

title: Multiply by 4
description: Multiply 4 times a number less than or equal to 10.

title: Intro to division
description: Use arrays and word problems to visualize division.

title: Ideal gas equation
description: In this tutorial, Sal shows you how to use the ideal gas equation in calculations.

title: Equivalent fractions
description: Learn how to create equivalent fractions using visuals.

title: States of matter follow-up
description: More on plasma and hydrogen bonds.

title: Vapor pressure
description: Vapor pressure, volatility, and evaporation.

title: Phase diagrams
description: Understanding and interpreting phase diagrams

title: Picture graphs
description: Read and interpret picture graphs.  Also, make some graphs of your own!

title: Elastic collisions and conservation of momentum
description: Categorizing the different types of collisions can be useful. In this lesson, we'll learn what it means for a collision to be elastic and what that tells us about the momentum and kinetic energy during the collision.

title: Calculating spring force
description: Practice finding the spring force using Hooke's law.

title: Calculating elastic potential energy
description: Practice calculating the elastic potential energy stored in a spring.

title: Spring potential energy and Hooke's law review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for spring potential energy and Hooke's law.  Understand how to analyze a spring force vs. displacement graph.

title: Calculating speed and mass using conservation of momentum
description: Practice applying the law of conservation of momentum to solve for masses or velocities for two interacting objects.

title: Gravitational field strength
description: Predict how gravitational field strength changes with radius and mass.

title: Conservation of energy
description: Learn about the law of conservation of energy, and how it can be useful for solving physics problems.

title: Elastic collisions review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for elastic collisions, including how to predict objects' final velocities.

title: Law of conservation of energy
description: Sal discusses how energy can't be created or destroyed in an isolated system, and works an example of how energy is transformed when a ball falls toward the Earth.

title: Inelastic collisions
description: Collisions can be elastic or inelastic. In this lesson, we'll learn what quantities are conserved and not conserved during inelastic collisions.

title: Impact of mass on orbital speed
description: Example question exploring how mass impacts orbital speed.

title: Conservation of energy: Predict changes in energy
description: Practice applying the conservation of energy to predict changes in kinetic energy, potential energy, and velocity.

title: Properties of inelastic and elastic collisions
description: Practice identifying properties of elastic and inelastic collisions.

title: Numbers 0 to 120
description: Learn the numbers from 0 to 120.

title: Bar graphs
description: Learn how to read and interpret bar graphs.

title: Picture graphs
description: Learn how to read and make picture graphs.

title: Addition and subtraction missing value problems
description: Learn how to solve problems like "___ - 37 = 48" where you don't know one of the values in an addition or subtraction equation.

title: Money
description: Learn how to count U.S. coins and dollars.

title: Introduction to electromagnetic waves
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn about the different categories of the electromagnetic spectrum; radio waves, microwaves, infrared, visible, ultraviolet, x-ray, and gamma ray. You'll also learn what it means for light to be polarized, and how polarized light can allow for the creation of 3D movies.

title: Conservation of energy: Numerical calculations
description: Practice applying the conservation of energy law to numerically solve for an unknown.

title: Newton's law of gravitation review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for Newton's law of gravity, including how to find the gravitational field strength.

title: Inelastic collision review
description: Review the key concepts and skills for inelastic collisions.  Understand how to determine if a collision is elastic or inelastic.

title: Conservation of energy review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for the conservation of energy, mechanical energy, and nonconservative work.

title: Center of mass and two-dimensional collisions
description: Learn about the center of mass and how to analyze momentum for collisions in two-dimensions.

title: Interference of electromagnetic waves
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how overlapping light waves can cause constructive and destructive interference. Some examples of light interference that will be discussed include Young's double slit interference, single slit interference, and thin film interference.

title: Predicting motion using the center of mass
description: Practice predicting the motion of an object using the center of mass of the system.

title: Relating power and energy
description: Practice applying the relationship between power and the rate of energy transfer.

title: Center of mass and two-dimensional collisions review
description: Review the key concepts, equations, and skills for the center of mass and two-dimensional collisions, including how to understand center of mass motion.

title: Introduction to rotational motion
description: Learn what angular displacement, angular velocity, and angular acceleration mean, as well as how they relate to their linear counterparts.

title: Power review
description: Review the key concepts and equations for power, including the difference between power and energy.

title: Angular and tangential acceleration
description: Practice thinking about the relationships between angular acceleration, tangential acceleration, and radius.

title: Reflection and refraction
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how to determine the angle of reflected light and the definition of specular and diffuse reflection. You'll also learn how to use Snell's law to determine the angle of a refracted light ray. Example problems dealing with the refraction of light rays will be solved. The topics of total internal reflection, critical angle, and dispersion will also be discussed.

title: Introduction to rotational motion review
description: Overview of key terms, equations, and skills for rotational motion, including the difference between angular and tangential acceleration.

title: Angular kinematics
description: Learn the relationships between angular displacement, angular velocity, and angular acceleration using the rotational kinematic formulas.

title: Using rotational kinematic formulas
description: Practical calculating time and angular quantities such as angular velocity, displacement, and acceleration using the kinematic formulas.

title: Angular kinematics review
description: Overview of equations and skills for angular kinematics, including how to choose the best angular kinematics formula.

title: Torque and equilibrium
description: Anyone who has ever opened a door has an intuitive understanding of torque. In this lesson, we'll explore why and how objects rotate using the concepts of torque and rotational equilibrium.

title: Introduction to simple harmonic motion
description: In this lesson, we'll develop some intuition for what a simple harmonic oscillator is, why they oscillate, and how to analyze and model the motion of spring-mass systems and simple pendulums.

title: Mirrors
description: In these videos and articles you'll learn how flat and curved/parabolic mirrors create images. The definitions of real and virtual images will be discussed. You'll also learn how to use the mirror equation to determine the image distance, magnification, image height, and object height when dealing with curved mirrors. The sign convention for positive and negative image distance, object distance, and focal length will be discussed.

title: Calculating torque
description: Practice calculating the clockwise or counterclockwise torque when a force is exerted on a bar that can rotate around an axis.

title: Simple harmonic motion: Finding frequency and period from graphs
description: Practice finding frequency and period from a graph of simple harmonic motion.

title: Equilibrium and applied force
description: Practice predicting where a force should be applied to keep a bar in rotational equilibrium.

title: Simple harmonic motion: Finding speed, velocity, and displacement from graphs
description: Practice finding speed, velocity, and distance traveled for an oscillator from graphs of simple harmonic motion.

title: Torque and equilibrium review
description: Review the concept of torque and how it is affected by the applied force and lever arm.

title: Rotational inertia and angular second law
description: In this lesson, we'll learn how the distribution of mass can impact how easily the angular velocity can be changed around an axis. This property is called rotational inertia.

title: Introduction to simple harmonic motion review
description: Overview of key terms, equations, and skills for simple harmonic motion, including how to analyze the force, displacement, velocity, and acceleration of an oscillator.

title: Lenses
description: Curved lenses help people see better. In this section you'll learn how to use ray tracings and the thin lens equation to find the location and size of images created by a curved lenses.

title: Simple harmonic motion in spring-mass systems
description: In this lesson, we'll learn more about how simple harmonic motion describes the motion of a mass on a spring.

title: Angular acceleration and angular second law
description: Practice applying the angular second law to predict the relationship between applied force and angular acceleration.

title: Subtracting 1s and 10s
description: Learn how to solve addition problems like 24-3 and 45-30.

title: Spring-mass systems: Calculating frequency, period, mass, and spring constant
description: Practice solving for the frequency, mass, period, and spring constant for a spring-mass system.

title: Rotational inertia and angular second law review
description: Overview of the key terms, equations, and skills related to rotational inertia, including how to analyze rotation inertia and how it relates to Newton's second law.

title: Analyzing graphs of spring-mass systems
description: Practice comparing motion graphs of two spring-mass systems.

title: Photons
description: Light can have wave-like or particle-like properties depending on the experiment being done. These "particles" of light are called photons. In this tutorial you'll learn about photon energy and momentum.

title: Rotational kinetic energy
description: Does a baseball have more kinetic energy if it is spinning? In this lesson, we'll learn how to determine the rotational kinetic energy of an object so we can figure out how much more energy the baseball has.

title: Simple harmonic motion in spring-mass systems review
description: Overview of key terms, equations, and skills for the simple harmonic motion of spring-mass systems, including comparing vertical and horizontal springs.

title: Simple pendulums
description: In this lesson, we'll learn more about how simple harmonic motion describes the motion of a simple pendulum.

title: Rotational kinetic energy
description: Practice comparing the rotational kinetic energy of two objects based on their shape and motion.

title: Period and frequency of simple pendulums
description: Practice finding the period, frequency, length and acceleration of gravity for a simple pendulum.

title: Atoms and electrons
description: Sometimes people draw atoms like little solar systems, but they're way stranger than that. In this section you'll learn how electrons can have wavelengths, jump orbitals, and emit photons while in an atom.

title: Rotational kinetic energy review
description: Overview of key terms, equations, and skills related to rotational kinetic energy, including the difference between rotational and translational kinetic energy.

title: Simple pendulum review
description: Overview of key terms, equations, and skills for simple pendulums, including how to analyze the forces on the mass.

title: Angular momentum and angular impulse
description: In this lesson, we'll learn about angular momentum and angular impulse, and how these quantities are related to translational (or linear) momentum.

title: Energy in simple harmonic oscillators
description: In this lesson, we'll learn about how the total energy, potential energy, and kinetic energy of a simple harmonic oscillator change over time.

title: Energy graphs for simple harmonic motion
description: Sal graphs elastic potential energy and kinetic energy for a mass on a spring and compares the total energy when with and without dissipative forces (friction).

title: Angular momentum calculations
description: Practice finding the angular momentum of spinning objects and objects with linear momentum.

title: Analyzing energy for a simple harmonic oscillator from graphs
description: Practice analyzing energy for a simple harmonic oscillator from velocity vs. time and position vs. time graphs.

title: Angular impulse calculations
description: Practice solving for angular momentum, time, or torque for a system with an external torque applied over a time interval.

title: Angular momentum and angular impulse review
description: Review how both rotating objects and objects with linear momentum can have angular momentum.  Recap how torque applied to and object over a time interval can change the angular momentum of an object.

title: Analyzing energy for a simple harmonic oscillator from data tables
description: Practice analyzing energy for a simple harmonic oscillator from tables of experimental data.

title: Conservation of angular momentum
description: Angular momentum is constant where there is no net torque, just like how linear momentum is constant when there is no net force. In this lesson, we'll learn about the conservation of angular momentum and how to apply the new conservation law to solve problems.

title: Energy of simple harmonic oscillator review
description: Overview of equations and skills for the energy of simple harmonic oscillators, including how to find the elastic potential energy and kinetic energy over time. Understand how total energy, kinetic energy, and potential energy are all related.

title: Comparing 3-digit numbers
description: Learn how to compare three-digit numbers by thinking about place value (hundreds, tens, and ones).

title: Conservation of angular momentum
description: How angular momentum is conserved within a system when there is no external torque.

title: Quantum numbers and orbitals
description: In this tutorial, we will see how the quantum numbers predict the orbitals available in different energy levels.

title: Predicting changes in momentum during collisions
description: Using the conservation of momentum to predict the change in angular momentum for an object or system during a collision.

title: Conservation of angular momentum calculations
description: Applying the conservation of angular momentum to collisions to calculate angular quantities such as angular velocity.

title: Conservation of angular momentum review
description: Review how angular momentum is conserved if there is no external torque applied to a system.  Specific scenarios are highlighted: system changing it rotational inertia, orbiting bodies, and rotational collisions.

title: Introduction to waves
description: In this lesson, you'll learn the definition of a wave and the difference between transverse and longitudinal waves.

title: Gravitational potential energy at large distances
description: Until this lesson, we have always assumed the gravitational field is uniform and potential energy is equal to mgh. Now we'll learn how to find the gravitational potential energy at large distances when these assumptions no longer hold.

title: Nuclear physics
description: In this tutorial, we will learn about radioactive decay, nuclear stability, and what is happening on a subatomic level during a nuclear reaction.

title: Gravitational potential energy at large distances
description: Learn how to calculate gravitational potential energy when we can no longer assume the gravitational field is uniform.

title: Identifying transverse and longitudinal waves
description: Practice identifying representations of transverse and longitudinal waves

title: Calculating gravitational potential energy of a system
description: Practice calculating the gravitational potential energy for a system of two masses.

title: Transverse and longitudinal waves review
description: Overview of key terms and skills for waves, including how to identify longitudinal and transverse waves.

title: Gravitational potential energy and conservation of angular momentum
description: Predict changes in gravitational potential energy and angular momentum for a system of two masses.

title: Wave characteristics
description: In this lesson, you'll learn the definition of the basic terms used to characterize waves such as amplitude, period, frequency, and wavelength.

title: Gravitational potential energy at large distances review
description: Review the equations and skills related to gravitational potential energy at large distances, including how to apply conservations laws to objects in orbit.

title: Characteristics of longitudinal and transverse waves
description: Practice identifying the characteristics of a longitudinal or transverse wave such as the wavelength, crest, and areas of compression.

title: Calculating wave speed, frequency, and wavelength
description: Practice using the wave speed equation for word problems to find the frequency and wavelength of a wave.

title: Calculating frequency and wavelength from displacement graphs
description: Practice using a displacement graph and wave speed to find the frequency and wavelength of a wave.

title: Wave energy from graphs
description: Practice comparing the energy of waves and wave pulses with different amplitudes, frequencies, wavelengths, and shapes.

title: Wave characteristics review
description: Review the characteristics of periodic transverse and longitudinal waves such as wavelength, crest, trough, amplitude, expansion, and compression.

title: Missing number within 20
description: Learn how to solve problems like "___ + 7 = 18" where you don't know one of the values in an addition or subtraction equation.

title: Length and size
description: Learn how to compare things by length. Measure objects with same-size length units without gaps or overlaps.

title: Word problems within 20
description: Learn how to solve addition and subtraction word problems. Numbers used are 20 or less.

title: Topic B: Lessons 13-15: Logarithms and equations
Predicting wave interference patterns
description: Practice predicting how two wave pulses interfere to form new wave patterns as they pass through each other.

title: Wave interference review
description: Review the key terms and skills related to wave interference, including how to predict wave interference patterns.

title: Standing waves
description: In this lesson, we'll discuss how and why standing waves occur, and well as how to determine the wavelength and frequency for a standing wave.

title: Wavelength and frequency for a standing wave
description: Practice finding standing wave frequencies and wavelength from a standing wave pattern.

title: Word problems with "more" and "fewer"
description: Learn how to solve word problems that use the words "more" and "fewer". Numbers used are 20 or less.

title: Calculating frequency for harmonics of a standing wave
description: Practice calculating the oscillation frequency for different harmonics of a standing wave.

title: Standing waves review
description: Review key terms and skills related to standing waves including how to find standing wave harmonics.

title: Introduction to sound
description: In this lesson, you'll see visualizations of sound waves, along with a visual definition of a sound wave's amplitude, period, frequency, and wavelength.

title: Intro to addition with 2-digit numbers
description: Learn how to add two-digit numbers. By the end of this tutorial, you'll be able to solve problems like 48+6 and 48+21. More advanced problems like 48+28 will be covered in a future tutorial.

title: Wavelength and frequency for sound waves  in tubes
description: Practicing calculating the wavelength and frequency of sound waves created in open and closed tubes.

title: Pressure and displacement of sound waves in tubes
description: Practice identifying nodes and antinodes for pressure and displacement from a standing wave diagram.

title: Introduction to sound review
description: Review the key terms and skills for sound waves, including how to identify the nodes and antinodes for standing waves in tubes.

title: Intro to addition with 2-digit numbers
description: Learn how to add two-digit numbers. By the end of this tutorial, you'll be able to solve problems like 48+6 and 48+21. More advanced problems like 48+28 will be covered in a future tutorial.

title: Beats and interference of sound waves
description: In this lesson, we'll discuss what happens when sound waves with different frequencies overlap.

title: Analyzing the interference of sound waves and beats
description: Practice analyzing patterns formed when two sound waves interfere.

title: Electric charge
description: In this lesson, we'll review protons and electrons and start discussing the properties of electric charge, including how charge is quantized.
